04480nam a22006735i 9780226403533DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226403533  a(DE-B1597)523453  a(OCoLC)979417616  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF1623.S35bJ67 2018 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a001.09032231 aStorm, Jason Ananda Josephson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Myth of Disenchantment :bMagic, Modernity, and the Birth of the Human Sciences /cJason Ananda Josephson Storm. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Enchanted (Post) Modernity -- tPart 1: God’s Shadow -- t2. Revenge of the Magicians -- t3. The Myth of Absence -- t4. The Shadow of God -- t5. The Decline of Magic: J. G. Frazer -- t6. The Revival of Magick: Aleister Crowley -- tPart 2: The Horrors of Metaphysics -- t7. The Black Tide: Mysticism, Rationality, and the German Occult Revival -- t8. Dialectic of Darkness: The Magical Foundations of Critical Theory -- t9. The Ghosts of Metaphysics: Logical Positivism and Disenchantment -- t10. The World of Enchantment; or, Max Weber at the End of History -- tConclusion: The Myth of Modernity -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA great many theorists have argued that the defining feature of modernity is that people no longer believe in spirits, myths, or magic. Jason Ā. Josephson-Storm argues that as broad cultural history goes, this narrative is wrong, as attempts to suppress magic have failed more often than they have succeeded. Even the human sciences have been more enchanted than is commonly supposed. But that raises the question: How did a magical, spiritualist, mesmerized Europe ever convince itself that it was disenchanted? Josephson-Storm traces the history of the myth of disenchantment in the births of philosophy, anthropology, sociology, folklore, psychoanalysis, and religious studies. Ironically, the myth of mythless modernity formed at the very time that Britain, France, and Germany were in the midst of occult and spiritualist revivals. Indeed, Josephson-Storm argues, these disciplines’ founding figures were not only aware of, but profoundly enmeshed in, the occult milieu; and it was specifically in response to this burgeoning culture of spirits and magic that they produced notions of a disenchanted world. By providing a novel history of the human sciences and their connection to esotericism, The Myth of Disenchantment dispatches with most widely held accounts of modernity and its break from the premodern past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMagic - History. 0aMagicxHistory. 0aMyth. 0aPhilosophy, Modern. 0aScience and magic. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aMax Weber.  adisenchantment.  aenlightenment.  ahistory of philosophy.  ahistory of the social sciences.  amagic.  amodernity.  amythology.  areligion.  areligious studies.  ascience.  awestern esotericism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226403533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226403533/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles